          <text>
                    <body>
                              <pb n="1"/>
                              <p rend="align(right)">
                                        <placeName>Mobile</placeName>
                                        <date>29<hi rend="sup">th</hi> Decr. 1850</date>
                              </p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">Dear Sir</p>
                              <p rend="indent(3)">Yours of <date>18<hi rend="sup">th</hi></date>
                                        reached me this morning<lb/> &amp; I am obliged to you for
                                        your free &amp; friendly com=<lb/>ments on my brochures,
                                        which I did not send you<lb/> with any desire of
                                                  <del>my</del> being noticed in the occident.<lb/>
                                        You had been so kind as reply to the queries which<lb/> I
                                        had propounded, &amp; as a matter of courtesy I sent<lb/>
                                        these essays to you, not hoping that you would coin<lb/>cide
                                        with me in opinion, but hoping they might show<lb/> you what
                                        the enemy were doing &amp; afford you some<lb/> material for
                                        reflection.</p>
                              <p>A letter is not the place to reopen this discussion. You<lb/>
                                        believe in the strict authenticity of the Pentateuch,
                                        which<lb/> I with <persName>Gesenius</persName>,
                                                  <persName>De Wette</persName>,
                                                  <persName>Eichhorn</persName>,
                                                  <persName>Munk</persName>,
                                                  <persName>Cohen</persName>, &amp;<lb/> many other
                                        first rate Hebrew scholars, do not, to say the<lb/> least
                                        the question is unsettled, while the Egyptian
                                        dis=<lb/>coveries go far I think to strengthen the party
                                        opposed<lb/> to you. Admitting the antiquity of the
                                        Pentateuch,<lb/> this is no proof of its historical
                                        accuracy—modern sci=<lb/>ence I think has clearly upset the
                                        plain &amp; simple account<lb/> of the Creation in Genesis,
                                        &amp; I think the Genealogies, &amp; Chro=<lb/>nology of the
                                        Hebrew text <del>is</del> are pretty generally abandoned
                                        by<lb/> scholars—<hi rend="underline">certainly</hi> the
                                        chronologies of <placeName>Egypt</placeName> &amp;
                                                  <placeName>China</placeName><lb/> destroy that of
                                        Genesis I think, &amp; this book <del>itself</del> has
                                        state<lb/>ments written itself irreconcilable with each
                                        other all<lb/> this of course you deny.</p>
                              <p>My object was not <hi rend="underline">theological</hi> discussion.
                                        I entered<lb/> this field because the Unity of Races could
                                        not be dis=<lb/>cussed apart from the Bible, &amp; I wished
                                        to cut loose what</p>
                              <pb n="2"/>
                              <p>I considered great <hi rend="underline">practical truths</hi> from
                                        the trammels<lb/> which find it. If there <hi
                                                  rend="underline">is</hi> a <hi rend="underline"
                                                  >gradation</hi> in Races, the<lb/> fact is too
                                        important to be smothered, by human<lb/> opinions.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">In reply to your comments on my note on<lb/> page
                                        40 of “Chronology” I need only say that if you will<lb/>
                                        recur to it you will see that you have been led into<lb/> an
                                        error by reading <persName>Moses</persName> instead of
                                                  <persName><hi rend="underline"
                                                  >Menes</hi></persName> the first<lb/> of the
                                        Pharaohs—I regard two facts as <add>?</add> which are<lb/>
                                        incompatible with <hi rend="underline">Genesis</hi> as we
                                        have it viz the Chronology—<lb/>&amp; the proof of distinct
                                        Races as far back as the 3d or 4th<lb/> Dynasties. Though
                                                  <hi rend="underline">exactness</hi> cannot be
                                        attained as<lb/> to the date of <persName><hi
                                                  rend="underline">Menes</hi></persName>, I think
                                                  <hi rend="underline">all</hi> Egyptologists
                                        place<lb/> him <del>far beyond</del> &amp; African <hi
                                                  rend="underline">Races</hi> far beyond your<lb/>
                                        date of the flood</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">I regret very much that on page 17 of
                                                  Phy<add>?</add> List of<lb/> Jews I have put words
                                        in your mouth which you<lb/> did not use. The latter part of
                                        the paragraph to<lb/> which you allude is from <persName><hi
                                                  rend="underline">Buchanan</hi></persName> &amp;
                                        the printer or<lb/> editor in
                                                  <placeName>Charleston</placeName> must have made
                                        the mistake. I<lb/> never saw the <hi rend="underline"
                                                  >proofs</hi>, &amp; this is but one of many
                                        blunders<lb/> they have made for me on different
                                        occasions.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)"><persName>Smyths</persName> critique on my book is
                                        too weak &amp; ungentlemanly<lb/> to deserve a reply.
                                                  <persName>Howes</persName> is not much better
                                        &amp; I replied<lb/> merely to keep the subject alive.
                                                  <persName>Bachmans</persName> book is a rare
                                        combi<lb/>nation of biggotry, talent, &amp; learning.
                                                  <persName>Agassiz</persName> &amp;
                                                  <persName>Morton</persName> have killed<lb/> him
                                        so dead that he can never kick again</p>
                              <p rend="indent(8)">very respectfully</p>
                              <p rend="indent(10)">your obt. servt</p>
                              <p rend="indent(10)">
                                        <persName role="author">J. C. Mott</persName>
                              </p>
                              <p>To <addressee>Isaac Leeser Esq</addressee></p>
                              <p rend="indent(2)">
                                        <placeName>Phia.</placeName>
                              </p>
